# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple/1-butanol] 1-Butanol occurs naturally as a minor product of the ethanol fermentation of sugars and other saccharides and is present in many foods and drinks.
[src:apple/1-butanol] It is also a permitted artificial flavorant in the United States, used in butter, cream, fruit, rum, whiskey, ice cream and ices, candy, baked goods, and cordials.
[src:apple/1-butanol] It is also used in a wide range of consumer products.
[src:apple/1-butanol] The largest use of 1-butanol is as an industrial intermediate, particularly for the manufacture of butyl acetate (itself an artificial flavorant and industrial solvent).
[src:apple/1-butanol] It is a petrochemical derived from propylene.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Estimated production figures for 1997 are: United States 784,000 tonnes; Western Europe 575,000 tonnes; Japan 225,000 tonnes.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Since the 1950s, most 1-butanol is produced by the hydroformylation of propene (oxo process) to preferentially form the butyraldehyde n-butanal.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Typical catalysts are based on cobalt and rhodium.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Butyraldehyde is then hydrogenated to produce butanol.
[src:apple/1-butanol] In former times, butanol was prepared from crotonaldehyde, which can be obtained from acetaldehyde.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Butanol can also be produced by fermentation of biomass by bacteria.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Prior to the 1950s, *Clostridium acetobutylicum* was used in industrial fermentation to produce butanol.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Research in the past few decades showed results of other microorganisms that can produce butanol through fermentation.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Butanol can be produced via furan hydrogenation over Pd or Pt catalyst at high temperature and high pressure.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Constituting 85% of its use, 1-butanol is mainly used in the production of varnishes.
[src:apple/1-butanol] It is a popular solvent, e.g. for nitrocellulose.
[src:apple/1-butanol] A variety of butanol derivatives are used as solvents, e.g. butoxyethanol or butyl acetate.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Many plasticizers are based on butyl esters, e.g., dibutyl phthalate.
[src:apple/1-butanol] The monomer butyl acrylate is used to produce polymers.
[src:apple/1-butanol] 1-Butanol has been proposed as a substitute for diesel fuel and gasoline.
[src:apple/1-butanol] It is produced in small quantities in nearly all fermentations (see fusel oil).
[src:apple/1-butanol] Clostridium produces much higher yields of butanol.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Research is underway to increase the biobutanol yield from biomass.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Butanol is considered as a potential biofuel (butanol fuel).
[src:apple/1-butanol] Butanol at 85 percent strength can be used in cars designed for gasoline without any change to the engine (unlike 85% ethanol), and it provides more energy for a given volume than ethanol, almost as much as gasoline.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Therefore, a vehicle using butanol would return fuel consumption more comparable to gasoline than ethanol.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Butanol can also be added to diesel fuel to reduce soot emissions.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Butan-1-ol occurs naturally as a result of carbohydrate fermentation in a number of alcoholic beverages, including beer, grape brandies, wine, and whisky.
[src:apple/1-butanol] It has been detected in the volatiles of hops, jack fruit, heat-treated milks, musk melon, cheese, southern pea seed, and cooked rice.
[src:apple/1-butanol] 1-Butanol is also formed during deep frying of corn oil, cottonseed oil, trilinolein, and triolein.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Butan-1-ol is one of the "fusel alcohols" (from the German for "bad liquor"), which include alcohols that have more than two carbon atoms and have significant solubility in water.
[src:apple/1-butanol] It is a natural component of many alcoholic beverages, albeit in low and variable concentrations.
[src:apple/1-butanol] It (along with similar fusel alcohols) is reputed to be responsible for severe hangovers, although experiments in animal models show no evidence for this.
[src:apple/1-butanol] The acute toxicity of 1-butanol is relatively low, with oral LD50 values of 790–4,360 mg/kg (rat; comparable values for ethanol are 7,000–15,000 mg/kg).
[src:apple/1-butanol] It is metabolized completely in vertebrates in a manner similar to ethanol: alcohol dehydrogenase converts 1-butanol to butyraldehyde; this is then converted to butyric acid by aldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Butyric acid can be fully metabolized to carbon dioxide and water by the β-oxidation pathway.
[src:apple/1-butanol] In the rat, only 0.03% of an oral dose of 2,000 mg/kg was excreted in the urine.
[src:apple/1-butanol] At sub-lethal doses, 1-butanol acts as a depressant of the central nervous system, similar to ethanol: one study in rats indicated that the intoxicating potency of 1-butanol is about 6 times higher than that of ethanol, possibly because of its slower transformation by alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Liquid 1-butanol, as is common with most organic solvents, is extremely irritating to the eyes; repeated contact with the skin can also cause irritation.
[src:apple/1-butanol] This is believed to be a generic effect of defatting.
[src:apple/1-butanol] No skin sensitization has been observed.
[src:apple/1-butanol] Irritation of the respiratory pathways occurs only at very high concentrations (>2,400 ppm).
[src:apple/1-butanol] With a flash point of 35 °C, 1-butanol presents a moderate fire hazard: it is slightly more flammable than kerosene or diesel fuel but less flammable than many other common organic solvents.
[src:apple/1-butanol] The depressant effect on the central nervous system (similar to ethanol intoxication) is a potential hazard when working with 1-butanol in enclosed spaces, although the odour threshold (0.2–30 ppm) is far below the concentration which would have any neurological effect.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] The compound **1-methylcyclopropene**, also known as **1-MCP**, is a cyclo­propene derivative used as a synthetic plant growth regulator.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] It is structurally related to the natural plant hormone ethylene and it is used commercially to slow down the ripening of fruit and to help maintain the freshness of cut flowers.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] The phenyl­lithium should be free of lithium halides.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] The corresponding reaction of allyl chloride and phenyl­lithium main affords cyclo­propyl­benzene.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] The mechanism of action of 1-MCP involves its tightly binding to the ethylene receptor in plants, thereby blocking the effects of ethylene (competitive inhibitor).
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] The compound 1-MCP is used commercially to maintain the freshness of ornamental plants and flowers and preventing the ripening of fruits.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] It is used in enclosed sites, such as coolers, truck trailers, greenhouses, storage facilities, and shipping containers.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] Under the brand name EthylBloc, 1-MCP was approved in 1999 by the U.S.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] Environmental Protection Agency for use on ornamental crops.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] For cut flowers, potted flowers, and bedding, nursery and foliage plants, 1-MCP prevents or delays wilting, leaf yellowing, opening, and death.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] Under the brand name SmartFresh, 1-MCP is used in the agriculture industry by growers, packers, and shippers to prevent or delay the natural ripening process.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] The use of 1-MCP in agricultural products including apples, kiwifruit, tomatoes, bananas, plums, persimmons, avocados, and melons has been approved and accepted for use in more than 34 countries including the European Union and the United States.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] Although benefiting from fresher produce and lower cost, the consumer however may be purchasing fruit that is older than expected.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] The compound 1-MCP is also being developed as a crop protection technique.
[src:apple/1-methylcyclopropene] By spraying 1-MCP on growing field crops during times of stress, the crops may be protected from moderate heat and drought conditions.
[src:apple/2-methyl-1-butanol] 2-Methyl-1-butanol is a component of many mixtures of commercial amyl alcohols.
[src:apple/2-methyl-1-butanol] For example, fusel alcohols like 2M1B are grain fermentation byproducts, and therefore trace amounts of 2M1B are present in many alcoholic beverages.
[src:apple/2-methyl-1-butanol] Also, it is one of the many components of the aroma of various fungi and fruit, e.g., the summer truffle, tomato, and cantaloupe.
[src:apple/2-methyl-1-butanol] 2-Methyl-1-butanol has been produced from glucose by genetically modified E. coli.
[src:apple/2-methyl-1-butanol] 2-Keto-3-methylvalerate, a precursor to threonine, is converted to the target alcohol by the sequential action of 2-keto acid decarboxylase and dehydrogenase.
[src:apple/2-methyl-1-butanol] It can be derived from fusel oil (because it occurs naturally in fruits such as grapes) or manufactured by either the oxo process or via the halogenation of pentane.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] Synthetic routes for the production of isovaleraldehyde vary.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] A small amount of 2,2-dimethylpropanal ((CH3)2C(CHO)CH3) side product is also generated.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] Another method of production involves the isomerization of isoprenol using CuO–ZnO as a catalyst.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] A mixture of isoprenol and prenol may also be used.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] Finally, in beer the compound is produced via a reaction between the amino acid leucine and reductones in the malt.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] As it can be derived from leucine, the occurrence of isovaleraldehyde is not limited to beer.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] The compound has found to be a flavor component in many different types of foods.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] It is described as having a malty flavor and has been found in cheese, coffee, chicken, fish, chocolate, olive oil, and tea.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] The compound is used as a reactant in the synthesis of a number of compounds.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] Notably it is used to synthesize tetramethylethylene, and is then converted to pinacol and pinacolone.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] Pinacolone itself is then used in synthesis for number of pesticides.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] Additionally, a range of pharmaceuticals, such as butizide, are synthesized from isovaleraldehyde and its corresponding acid.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] It is a common reagent or building block in organic synthesis.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] Acid-catalyzed cyclic trimerization of Isovaleraldehyde gives 2,4,6-Triisobutyl-1,3,5-trioxane [68165-40-2].
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] This is a flavouring agent that can be used in confectionary, tobacco, and other foodstuffs, toothpastes and the like.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] It is described as imparting a creamy, dairy, vanilla chocolate and berry flavour.
[src:apple/3-methylbutanal] According to IFF, isovaleraldehyde is used as a food flavorant additive.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] Isoamyl acetate occurs naturally in many plants, including apple, banana, coffee, grape, guava, lychee, papaya, peach, pomegranate, and tomato.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] It is also released by fermentation processes, including those used for making beer, sake, cognac, and whisky.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] Isoamyl acetate is released by a honey bee's sting apparatus where it serves as a pheromone beacon to attract other bees and provoke them to sting.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] Isoamyl acetate is prepared by the acid-catalyzed reaction (Fischer esterification) between isoamyl alcohol and glacial acetic acid as shown in the reaction equation below.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] Typically, sulfuric acid is used as the catalyst.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] Alternatively, *p*-toluenesulfonic acid or an acidic ion exchange resin can be used as the catalyst.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] It is also produced synthetically by the rectification of amyl acetate.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] Isoamyl acetate is used to confer banana or pear flavor in foods such as circus peanuts, Juicy Fruit and pear drops.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] *Banana oil* and *pear oil* commonly refer to a solution of isoamyl acetate in ethanol that is used as an artificial flavor.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] It is also used as a solvent for some varnishes, oil paints, and nitrocellulose lacquers.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] As a solvent and carrier for materials such as nitrocellulose, it was extensively used in the aircraft industry for stiffening and wind-proofing fabric flying surfaces, where it and its derivatives were generally known as 'aircraft dope'.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] Now that most aircraft wings are made of metal, such use is mostly limited to historically accurate reproductions and scale models.
[src:apple/3-methylbutyl-acetate] Because of its intense, pleasant odor and its low toxicity, isoamyl acetate is used to test the effectiveness of respirators or gas masks.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] An **accessory fruit** is a fruit that contains tissue derived from plant parts other than the ovary.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] In other words, the flesh of the fruit develops not from the floral ovary, but from some adjacent tissue exterior to the carpel (for example, from receptacles or sepal).
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] As a general rule, the accessory fruit is a combination of several floral organs, including the ovary.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] In contrast, true fruit forms exclusively from the ovary of the flower.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] Accessory fruits are usually indehiscent, meaning that they do not split open to release seeds when they have reached maturity.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] Fruit with fleshy seeds, such as pomegranate or mamoncillo, are not considered to be accessory fruits.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] The part of apples and pears that is consumed is, in fact, the hypanthium.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] The ovary is the papery core that surrounds the apple seeds.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] As the hypanthium ripens it forms the edible tissues.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] For roses, the hypanthium is the tissue that composes the edible part of rosehips.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] Roses and apples are both members of the Rosaceae family; the fact that they have similar fruit morphology is a major consideration in placing them in the same taxonomic family.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] The edible part of the strawberry is formed, as part of the ripening process, from the receptacle of the strawberry flower.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] The true fruits (hence, containing the seeds) are the roughly 200 pips (which are, technically, achenes, a true fruit that contains a single seed from a single ovary).
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] These pips dot the exterior of the strawberry.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] The cashew apple is an oval- or pear-shaped structure that develops from the pedicel and the receptacle of the cashew flower and is technically called a hypocarpium.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] It ripens into a yellow or red structure about 5–11 cm (2–4+1⁄4 in) long.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] The true fruit of the cashew tree is a kidney–shaped drupe that grows at the end of the cashew apple; the seed inside this drupe is the cashew nut of commerce.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] The pineapple is formed when 50 to 200 unpollinated flowers coalesce in a spiral arrangement— the flowers form individually and then fuse as a single 'multiple fruit'.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] The ovaries develop into berries and the fruit forms around an intercalary spike.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] The intercalary inflorescence (cluster of flowers) results when the terminal cluster of flowers are left behind by the growth of the main axis of the plant.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] Each polygonal area on the pineapple's surface is an individual flower.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] Current research has proposed that a single class of genes may be responsible for regulating accessory fruit formation and ripening.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] A study using strawberries concluded that hormone signaling pathways involving gibberellic acid and auxin affect gene expression, and contribute to the initiation of accessory fruit development.
[src:apple/accessory-fruit] Metabolic modifications in different developing accessory fruit tissues are due to the varied distributions of compounds such as triterpenoids and steroids.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has listed acetaldehyde as a Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxins with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In 1835, Liebig named it "aldehyde", and in the middle of the century the name was altered to "acetaldehyde".
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In 2013, global production was about 438,000 tonnes.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Before 1962, ethanol and acetylene were the major sources of acetaldehyde.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Since then, ethylene is the dominant feedstock.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In the 1970s, the world capacity of the Wacker-Hoechst direct oxidation process exceeded two million tonnes annually.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Smaller quantities can be prepared by the partial oxidation of ethanol in an exothermic reaction.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] This process typically is conducted over a silver catalyst at about 500–650 °C (950–1,200 °F).
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] This method is one of the oldest routes for the industrial preparation of acetaldehyde.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Prior to the Wacker process and the availability of cheap ethylene, acetaldehyde was produced by the hydration of acetylene.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The mechanism involves the intermediacy of vinyl alcohol, which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The reaction is conducted at 90–95 °C (194–203 °F), and the acetaldehyde formed is separated from water and mercury and cooled to 25–30 °C (77–86 °F).
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In the wet oxidation process, iron(III) sulfate is used to reoxidize the mercury back to the mercury(II) salt.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The resulting iron(II) sulfate is oxidized in a separate reactor with nitric acid.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The enzyme Acetylene hydratase discovered in the strictly anaerobic bacterium *Pelobacter acetylenicus* can catalyze an analogous reaction without involving any compounds of mercury.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] However, it has thus far not been brought to any large-scale or commercial use.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In this endothermic process, ethanol vapor is passed at 260–290 °C over a copper-based catalyst.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The process was once attractive because of the value of the hydrogen coproduct, but in modern times is not economically viable.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The hydroformylation of methanol with catalysts like cobalt, nickel, or iron salts also produces acetaldehyde, although this process is of no industrial importance.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Similarly noncompetitive, acetaldehyde arises from synthesis gas with modest selectivity.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The equilibrium constant is 6×10−7 at room temperature, thus that the relative amount of the enol form in a sample of acetaldehyde is very small.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] At room temperature, acetaldehyde (CH3CH=O) is more stable than vinyl alcohol (CH2=CHOH) by 42.7 kJ/mol: Overall the keto-enol tautomerization occurs slowly but is catalyzed by acids.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Photo-induced keto-enol tautomerization is viable under atmospheric or stratospheric conditions.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] This photo-tautomerization is relevant to the Earth's atmosphere, because vinyl alcohol is thought to be a precursor to carboxylic acids in the atmosphere.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a common electrophile in organic synthesis.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In addition reactions acetaldehyde is prochiral.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] It is used primarily as a source of the "CH3C+H(OH)" synthon in aldol reactions and related condensation reactions.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Grignard reagents and organolithium compounds react with MeCHO to give hydroxyethyl derivatives.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In one of the more spectacular addition reactions, formaldehyde in the presence of calcium hydroxide adds to MeCHO to give pentaerythritol, C(CH2OH)4 and formate.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In a Strecker reaction, acetaldehyde condenses with cyanide and ammonia to give, after hydrolysis, the amino acid alanine.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can condense with amines to yield imines; for example, with cyclohexylamine to give *N*-ethylidenecyclohexylamine.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] These imines can be used to direct subsequent reactions like an aldol condensation.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] It is also a building block in the synthesis of heterocyclic compounds.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In one example, it converts, upon treatment with ammonia, to 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine ("aldehyde-collidine").
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Three molecules of acetaldehyde condense to form "paraldehyde", a cyclic trimer containing C-O single bonds.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Similarly condensation of four molecules of acetaldehyde give the cyclic molecule metaldehyde.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Paraldehyde can be produced in good yields, using a sulfuric acid catalyst.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Metaldehyde is only obtained in a few percent yield and with cooling, often using HBr rather than H2SO4 as the catalyst.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] At −40 °C (−40 °F) in the presence of acid catalysts, polyacetaldehyde is produced.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] There are two stereomers of paraldehyde and four of metaldehyde.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The German chemist Valentin Hermann Weidenbusch (1821–1893) synthesized paraldehyde in 1848 by treating acetaldehyde with acid (either sulfuric or nitric acid) and cooling to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] He found it quite remarkable that when paraldehyde was *heated* with a trace of the same acid, the reaction went the other way, recreating acetaldehyde.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Although vinyl alcohol is a tautomeric form of acetaldehyde (§ Tautomerization to vinyl alcohol), polyvinyl alcohol cannot be produced from acetaldehyde.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde forms a stable acetal upon reaction with ethanol under conditions that favor dehydration.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The product, CH3CH(OCH2CH3)2, is formally named 1,1-diethoxyethane but is commonly referred to as "acetal".
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] This can cause confusion as "acetal" is more commonly used to describe compounds with the functional groups RCH(OR')2 or RR'C(OR'')2 rather than referring to this specific compound — in fact, 1,1-diethoxyethane is also described as the diethyl acetal of acetaldehyde.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a precursor to vinylphosphonic acid, which is used to make adhesives and ion conductive membranes.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In the liver, the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase oxidizes ethanol into acetaldehyde, which is then further oxidized into harmless acetic acid by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] These two oxidation reactions are coupled with the reduction of NAD+ to NADH.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In the brain, the enzyme catalase is primarily responsible for oxidizing ethanol to acetaldehyde, and alcohol dehydrogenase plays a minor role.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The last steps of alcoholic fermentation in bacteria, plants, and yeast involve the conversion of pyruvate into acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide by the enzyme pyruvate decarboxylase, followed by the conversion of acetaldehyde into ethanol.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The latter reaction is again catalyzed by an alcohol dehydrogenase, now operating in the opposite direction.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Many East Asian people have an ALDH2 mutation which makes them significantly less efficient at oxidizing acetaldehyde.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] On consuming alcohol, their bodies tend to accumulate excessive amounts of acetaldehyde, causing the so-called alcohol flush reaction.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] They develop a characteristic flush on the face and body, along with "nausea, headache and general physical discomfort".
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Ingestion of the drug disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2, leads to a similar reaction .
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Traditionally, acetaldehyde was mainly used as a precursor to acetic acid.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] This application has declined because acetic acid is produced more efficiently from methanol by the Monsanto and Cativa processes.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an important precursor to pyridine derivatives, pentaerythritol, and crotonaldehyde.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Urea and acetaldehyde combine to give a useful resin.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetic anhydride reacts with acetaldehyde to give ethylidene diacetate, a precursor to vinyl acetate, which is used to produce polyvinyl acetate.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The global market for acetaldehyde is declining.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Demand has been impacted by changes in the production of plasticizer alcohols, which has shifted because *n*-butyraldehyde is less often produced from acetaldehyde, instead being generated by hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Likewise, acetic acid, once produced from acetaldehyde, is made predominantly by the lower-cost methanol carbonylation process.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The impact on demand has led to increase in prices and thus slowdown in the market.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] China is the largest consumer of acetaldehyde in the world, accounting for almost half of global consumption in 2012.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Major use has been the production of acetic acid.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Other uses such as pyridines and pentaerythritol are expected to grow faster than acetic acid, but the volumes are not large enough to offset the decline in acetic acid.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] As a consequence, overall acetaldehyde consumption in China may grow slightly at 1.6% per year through 2018.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Western Europe is the second-largest consumer of acetaldehyde worldwide, accounting for 20% of world consumption in 2012.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] As with China, the Western European acetaldehyde market is expected to increase only very slightly at 1% per year during 2012–2018.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] However, Japan could emerge as a potential consumer for acetaldehyde in the next five years due to newfound use in commercial production of butadiene.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The supply of butadiene has been volatile in Japan and the rest of Asia.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] This should provide the much needed boost to the flat market, as of 2013.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The threshold limit value is 25 ppm (STEL/ceiling value) and the MAK (Maximum Workplace Concentration) is 50 ppm.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] At 50 ppm acetaldehyde, no irritation or local tissue damage in the nasal mucosa is observed.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] When taken up by the organism, acetaldehyde is metabolized rapidly in the liver to acetic acid.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Only a small proportion is exhaled unchanged.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] After intravenous injection, the half-life in the blood is approximately 90 seconds.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Many serious cases of acute intoxication have been recorded.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde naturally breaks down in the human body.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an irritant of the skin, eyes, mucous membranes, throat, and respiratory tract.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] This occurs at concentrations as low as 1000 ppm.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Symptoms of exposure to this compound include nausea, vomiting, and headache.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] These symptoms may not happen immediately.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The perception threshold for acetaldehyde in air is in the range between 0.07 and 0.25 ppm.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] At such concentrations, the fruity odor of acetaldehyde is apparent.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Conjunctival irritations have been observed after a 15-minute exposure to concentrations of 25 and 50 ppm, but transient conjunctivitis and irritation of the respiratory tract have been reported after exposure to 200 ppm acetaldehyde for 15 minutes.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In addition, acetaldehyde is damaging to DNA and causes abnormal muscle development as it binds to proteins.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde induces DNA interstrand crosslinks, a form of DNA damage.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] These can be repaired by either of two replication-coupled DNA repair pathways.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The first is referred to as the FA pathway, because it employs gene products defective in Fanconi's anemia patients.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] This repair pathway results in increased mutation frequency and altered mutational spectrum.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The second repair pathway requires replication fork convergence, breakage of the acetaldehyde crosslink, translesion synthesis by a Y-family DNA polymerase and homologous recombination.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] People with a genetic deficiency for the enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetic acid may have a greater risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] A study of 818 heavy drinkers found that those exposed to more acetaldehyde than normal through a genetic variant of the gene encoding for ADH1C, ADH1C*1, are at greater risk of developing cancers of the upper gastrointestinal tract and liver.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The drug disulfiram (Antabuse) inhibits acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, an enzyme that oxidizes the compound into acetic acid.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Metabolism of ethanol forms acetaldehyde before acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms acetic acid, but with the enzyme inhibited, acetaldehyde accumulates.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] If one consumes ethanol while taking disulfiram, the hangover effect of ethanol is felt more rapidly and intensely (disulfiram-alcohol reaction).
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] As such, disulfiram is sometimes used as a deterrent for alcoholics wishing to stay sober.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a potential contaminant in workplace, indoors, and ambient environments.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Moreover, the majority of humans spend more than 90% of their time in indoor environments, increasing any exposure and the risk to human health.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] In a study in France, the mean indoor concentration of acetaldehydes measured in 16 homes was approximately seven times higher than the outside acetaldehyde concentration.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The living room had a mean of 18.1±17.5 μg m−3 and the bedroom was 18.2±16.9 μg m−3, whereas the outdoor air had a mean concentration of 2.3±2.6 μg m−3.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] It has been concluded that volatile organic compounds (VOC) such as benzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, toluene, and xylenes have to be considered priority pollutants with respect to their health effects.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] It has been pointed that in renovated or completely new buildings, the VOCs concentration levels are often several orders of magnitude higher.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The main sources of acetaldehydes in homes include building materials, laminate, PVC flooring, varnished wood flooring, and varnished cork/pine flooring (found in the varnish, not the wood).
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] It is also found in plastics, oil-based and water-based paints, in composite wood ceilings, particle-board, plywood, treated pine wood, and laminated chipboard furniture.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The use of acetaldehyde is widespread in different industries, and it may be released into waste water or the air during production, use, transportation and storage.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Sources of acetaldehyde include fuel combustion emissions from stationary internal combustion engines and power plants that burn fossil fuels, wood, or trash, oil and gas extraction, refineries, cement kilns, lumber and wood mills and paper mills.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also present in automobile and diesel exhaust.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] As a result, acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxics with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Natural tobacco polysaccharides, including cellulose, have been shown to be the primary precursors making acetaldehyde a significant constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] It has been demonstrated to have a synergistic effect with nicotine in rodent studies of addiction.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke; it is dissolved into the saliva while smoking.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde has been found in cannabis smoke.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] This finding emerged through the use of new chemical techniques that demonstrated the acetaldehyde present was causing DNA damage in laboratory settings.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Many microbes produce acetaldehyde from ethanol, but they have a lower capacity to eliminate the acetaldehyde, which can lead to the accumulation of acetaldehyde in saliva, stomach acid, and intestinal contents.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Fermented food and many alcoholic beverages can also contain significant amounts of acetaldehyde.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde, derived from mucosal or microbial oxidation of ethanol, tobacco smoke, and diet, appears to act as a cumulative carcinogen in the upper digestive tract of humans.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] According to European Commission's Scientific Committee on Consumer Safety's (SCCS) "Opinion on Acetaldehyde" (2012) the cosmetic products special risk limit is 5 mg/L and acetaldehyde should not be used in mouth-washing products.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can be produced by the photo-oxidation of polyethylene terephthalate (PET), via a Type II Norrish reaction.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] Although the levels produced by this process are minute acetaldehyde has an exceedingly low taste/odor threshold of around 20–40 ppb and can cause an off-taste in bottled water.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The level at which an average consumer could detect acetaldehyde is still considerably lower than any toxicity.
[src:apple/acetaldehyde] The yeast *Candida albicans* in patients with potentially carcinogenic oral diseases has been shown to produce acetaldehyde in quantities sufficient to cause problems.
[src:apple/apple] An **apple** is the round, edible fruit of an apple tree (*Malus* spp.).
[src:apple/apple] Fruit trees of the **orchard** or **domestic apple** (***Malus domestica***), the most widely grown in the genus, are cultivated worldwide.
[src:apple/apple] The tree originated in Central Asia, where its wild ancestor, *Malus sieversii*, is still found.
[src:apple/apple] Apples have been grown for thousands of years in Eurasia before they were introduced to North America by European colonists.
[src:apple/apple] Apples have cultural significance in many mythologies (including Norse and Greek) and religions (such as Christianity in Europe).
[src:apple/apple] Apples grown from seeds tend to be very different from those of their parents, and the resultant fruit frequently lacks desired characteristics.
[src:apple/apple] For commercial purposes, including botanical evaluation, apple cultivars are propagated by clonal grafting onto rootstocks.
[src:apple/apple] Apple trees grown without rootstocks tend to be larger and much slower to fruit after planting.
[src:apple/apple] Rootstocks are used to control the speed of growth and the size of the resulting tree, allowing for easier harvesting.
[src:apple/apple] There are more than 7,500 cultivars of apples.
[src:apple/apple] Different cultivars are bred for various tastes and uses, including cooking, eating raw, and cider or apple juice production.
[src:apple/apple] Trees and fruit are prone to fungal, bacterial, and pest problems, which can be controlled by a number of organic and non-organic means.
[src:apple/apple] In 2010, the fruit's genome was sequenced as part of research on disease control and selective breeding in apple production.
[src:apple/apple] The word *apple* is derived from Old English *æppel*, meaning "fruit", not specifically the apple.
[src:apple/apple] That in turn is descended from the Proto-Germanic noun **aplaz*, descended in turn from Proto-Indo-European **h₂ébōl*.
[src:apple/apple] The apple tree is deciduous, generally standing from 2 to 4.5 metres (6 to 15 feet) tall in cultivation and up to 15 m (49 ft) in the wild, though more typically 2 to 10 m (6.5 to 33 ft).
[src:apple/apple] When cultivated, the size, shape and branch density are determined by rootstock selection and trimming method.
[src:apple/apple] Apple trees may naturally have a rounded to erect crown with a dense canopy of leaves.
[src:apple/apple] The bark of the trunk is dark gray or gray-brown, but young branches are reddish or dark-brown with a smooth texture.
[src:apple/apple] Young twigs are covered in fine downy hairs; they become hairless when older.
[src:apple/apple] The buds are egg-shaped and dark red or purple in color; they range in size from 3 to 5mm, but are usually less than 4mm.
[src:apple/apple] When emerging from the buds, the leaves are *convolute*, meaning that their edges overlap each other.
[src:apple/apple] Leaves can be simple ovals (elliptic), medium or wide in width, somewhat egg-shaped with the wider portion toward their base (ovate), or even with sides that are more parallel to each other instead of curved (oblong) with a narrow pointed end.
[src:apple/apple] The edges have broadly-angled teeth, but do not have lobes.
[src:apple/apple] The top surface of the leaves are *glabrescent*, almost hairless, while the undersides are densely covered in fine hairs.
[src:apple/apple] The leaves are attached alternately by short leaf stems 1-to-3.5 cm (1⁄2-to-1+1⁄2 in) long.
[src:apple/apple] Blossoms are produced in spring simultaneously with the budding of the leaves and are produced on spurs and some long shoots.
[src:apple/apple] When the flower buds first begin to open the petals are rose-pink and fade to white or light pink when fully open with each flower 3-to-4-centimeter (1-to-1+1⁄2-inch) in diameter.
[src:apple/apple] The five-petaled flowers are group in an inflorescence consisting of a cyme with 3–7 flowers.
[src:apple/apple] The central flower of the inflorescence is called the "king bloom"; it opens first and can develop a larger fruit.
[src:apple/apple] Open apple blossoms are damaged by even brief exposures to temperatures −2 °C (28 °F) or less, although the overwintering wood and buds are hardy down to −40 °C (−40 °F).
[src:apple/apple] The fruit is a pome that matures in late summer or autumn.
[src:apple/apple] The true fruits or carpels are the harder interior chambers inside the apple's core.
[src:apple/apple] There are usually five carpels inside an apple, but there may be as few as three.
[src:apple/apple] Each of the chambers contains one or two seeds.
[src:apple/apple] The edible flesh is formed from the receptacle at the base of the flower.
[src:apple/apple] The seeds are egg- to pear-shaped and may be colored from light brown or tan to a very dark brown, often with red shades or even purplish-black.
[src:apple/apple] The five sepals remain attached and stand out from the surface of the apple.
[src:apple/apple] The size of the fruit varies widely between cultivars, but generally has a diameter between 2.5 and 12 cm (1 and 5 in).
[src:apple/apple] The shape is quite variable and may be nearly round, elongated, conical, or short and wide.
[src:apple/apple] The groundcolor of ripe apples is yellow, green, yellow-green or whitish yellow.
[src:apple/apple] The overcolor of ripe apples can be orange-red, pink-red, red, purple-red or brown-red.
[src:apple/apple] The skin may be wholly or partly russeted, making it rough and brown.
[src:apple/apple] The skin is covered in a protective layer of epicuticular wax.
[src:apple/apple] The skin may also be marked with scattered dots.
[src:apple/apple] The flesh is generally pale yellowish-white, though it can be pink, yellow or green.
[src:apple/apple] Apples can have any amount of overcolor, a darker tint over a pale groundcolor.
[src:apple/apple] The apple as a species has more than 100 alternative scientific names, or synonyms.
[src:apple/apple] In modern times, *Malus pumila* and *Malus domestica* are the two main names in use.
[src:apple/apple] *M. pumila* is the older name, but *M. domestica* has become much more commonly used starting in the 21st century, especially in the western world.
[src:apple/apple] Two proposals were made to make *M. domestica* a conserved name: the earlier proposal was voted down by the Committee for Vascular Plants of the IAPT in 2014, but in April 2017 the Committee decided, with a narrow majority, that the newly popular name should be conserved.
[src:apple/apple] The General Committee of the IAPT decided in June 2017 to approve this change, officially conserving *M. domestica*.
[src:apple/apple] Nevertheless, some works published after 2017 still use *M. pumila* as the correct name, under an alternate taxonomy.
[src:apple/apple] When first classified by Linnaeus in 1753, the pears, apples, and quinces were combined into one genus that he named *Pyrus* and he named the apple as *Pyrus malus*.
[src:apple/apple] However, the botanist Philip Miller published an alternate classification in *The Gardeners Dictionary*, with the apple species separated from *Pyrus*, in 1754.
[src:apple/apple] He did not clearly indicate that by *Malus pumila* he meant the domesticated apple; nonetheless, the term was used as such by many botanists.
[src:apple/apple] When Moritz Balthasar Borkhausen published his scientific description of the apple in 1803 it may have been a new combination of *P. malus* var.
[src:apple/apple] *domestica*, but this was not directly referenced by Borkhausen.
[src:apple/apple] *domestica* for the apple was by Georg Adolf Suckow in 1786.
[src:apple/apple] Apples are diploid, with two sets of chromosomes per cell (though triploid cultivars, with three sets, are not uncommon), have 17 chromosomes and an estimated genome size of approximately 650 Mb.
[src:apple/apple] Several whole genome sequences have been completed and made available.
[src:apple/apple] The first one in 2010 was based on the diploid cultivar 'Golden Delicious'.
[src:apple/apple] However, this first whole genome sequence contained several errors, in part owing to the high degree of heterozygosity in diploid apples which, in combination with an ancient genome duplication, complicated the assembly.
[src:apple/apple] Recently, double- and trihaploid individuals have been sequenced, yielding whole genome sequences of higher quality.
[src:apple/apple] The first whole genome assembly was estimated to contain around 57,000 genes, though the more recent genome sequences support estimates between 42,000 and 44,700 protein-coding genes.
[src:apple/apple] The availability of whole genome sequences has provided evidence that the wild ancestor of the cultivated apple most likely is *Malus sieversii*.
[src:apple/apple] Re-sequencing of multiple accessions has supported this, while also suggesting extensive introgression from *Malus sylvestris* following domestication.
[src:apple/apple] Central Asia is generally considered the center of origin for apples due to the genetic variability in specimens there.
[src:apple/apple] The wild ancestor of *Malus domestica* was *Malus sieversii*, found growing wild in the mountains of Central Asia in southern Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and northwestern China.
[src:apple/apple] Cultivation of the species, most likely beginning on the forested flanks of the Tian Shan mountains, progressed over a long period of time and permitted secondary introgression of genes from other species into the open-pollinated seeds.
[src:apple/apple] Significant exchange with *Malus sylvestris*, the crabapple, resulted in populations of apples being more related to crabapples than to the more morphologically similar progenitor *Malus sieversii*.
[src:apple/apple] In strains without recent admixture the contribution of the latter predominates.
[src:apple/apple] Only the *M. sieversii* trees growing on the western side of the Tian Shan mountains contributed genetically to the domesticated apple, not the isolated population on the eastern side.
[src:apple/apple] Chinese soft apples, such as *M. asiatica* and *M. prunifolia*, have been cultivated as dessert apples for more than 2,000 years in China.
[src:apple/apple] These are thought to be hybrids between *M. baccata* and *M. sieversii* in Kazakhstan.
[src:apple/apple] Among the traits selected for by human growers are size, fruit acidity, color, firmness, and soluble sugar.
[src:apple/apple] Unusually for domesticated fruits, the wild *M. sieversii* origin is only slightly smaller than the modern domesticated apple.
[src:apple/apple] At the Sammardenchia-Cueis site near Udine in Northeastern Italy, seeds from some form of apples have been found in material carbon dated to between 6570 and 5684 BCE.
[src:apple/apple] Genetic analysis has not yet been successfully used to determine whether such ancient apples were wild *Malus sylvestris* or *Malus domesticus* containing *Malus sieversii* ancestry.
[src:apple/apple] It is hard to distinguish in the archeological record between foraged wild apples and apple plantations.
[src:apple/apple] There is indirect evidence of apple cultivation in the third millennium BCE in the Middle East.
[src:apple/apple] There is direct evidence, apple cores, dated to the 10th century BCE from a Judean site between the Sinai and Negev.
[src:apple/apple] There was substantial apple production in European classical antiquity, and grafting was certainly known then.
[src:apple/apple] Grafting is an essential part of modern domesticated apple production, to be able to propagate the best cultivars; it is unclear when apple tree grafting was invented.
[src:apple/apple] The Roman writer Pliny the Elder describes a method of storage for apples from his time in the 1st century.
[src:apple/apple] He says they should be placed in a room with good air circulation from a north facing window on a bed of straw, chaff, or mats with windfalls kept separately.
[src:apple/apple] These methods extend the shelf life of fresh apples, but refrigeration is still required.
[src:apple/apple] Even sturdy winter varieties only keep well until December in cool climates.
[src:apple/apple] For longer storage medieval Europeans strung up cored and peeled apples to dry, either whole or sliced into rings.
[src:apple/apple] Of the many Old World plants that the Spanish introduced to Chiloé Archipelago in the 16th century, apple trees became particularly well adapted.
[src:apple/apple] Apples were introduced to North America by colonists in the 17th century, and the first named apple cultivar was introduced in Boston by Reverend William Blaxton in 1640.
[src:apple/apple] The only apples native to North America are crab apples.
[src:apple/apple] Apple cultivars brought as seed from Europe were spread along Native American trade routes, as well as being cultivated on colonial farms.
[src:apple/apple] An 1845 United States apples nursery catalogue sold 350 of the "best" cultivars, showing the proliferation of new North American cultivars by the early 19th century.
[src:apple/apple] In the 20th century, irrigation projects in Eastern Washington began and allowed the development of the multibillion-dollar fruit industry, of which the apple is the leading product.
[src:apple/apple] Until the 20th century, farmers stored apples in frostproof cellars during the winter for their own use or for sale.
[src:apple/apple] Improved transportation of fresh apples by train and road replaced the necessity for storage.
[src:apple/apple] Controlled atmosphere facilities are used to keep apples fresh year-round.
[src:apple/apple] Controlled atmosphere facilities use high humidity, low oxygen, and controlled carbon dioxide levels to maintain fruit freshness.
[src:apple/apple] They were first researched at Cambridge University in the 1920s and first used in the United States in the 1950s.
[src:apple/apple] However, apples must be propagated asexually to obtain cuttings with the characteristics of the parent.
[src:apple/apple] This is because seedling apples do not "breed true", instead they are "extreme heterozygotes", i.e. rather than resembling their parents, seedlings are all different from each other and from their parents.
[src:apple/apple] Triploid cultivars have an additional reproductive barrier in that three sets of chromosomes cannot be divided evenly during meiosis, yielding unequal segregation of the chromosomes (aneuploids).
[src:apple/apple] Even in the case when a triploid plant can produce a seed (apples are an example), it occurs infrequently, and seedlings rarely survive.
[src:apple/apple] Because apples are not true breeders when planted as seeds, propagation usually involves grafting of cuttings.
[src:apple/apple] The rootstock used for the bottom of the graft can be selected to produce trees of a large variety of sizes, as well as changing the winter hardiness, insect and disease resistance, and soil preference of the resulting tree.
[src:apple/apple] Dwarf rootstocks can be used to produce very small trees (less than 3.0 m or 10 ft high at maturity), which bear fruit many years earlier in their life cycle than full size trees, and are easier to harvest.
[src:apple/apple] Dwarf rootstocks for apple trees can be traced as far back as 300 BCE, to the area of Persia and Asia Minor.
[src:apple/apple] Alexander the Great sent samples of dwarf apple trees to Aristotle's Lyceum.
[src:apple/apple] Dwarf rootstocks became common by the 15th century and later went through several cycles of popularity and decline throughout the world.
[src:apple/apple] The majority of the rootstocks used to control size in apples were developed in England in the early 1900s.
[src:apple/apple] The East Malling Research Station conducted extensive research into rootstocks, and their rootstocks are given an "M" prefix to designate their origin.
[src:apple/apple] Rootstocks marked with an "MM" prefix are Malling-series cultivars later crossed with trees of 'Northern Spy' in Merton, England.
[src:apple/apple] Most new apple cultivars originate as seedlings, which either arise by chance or are bred by deliberately crossing cultivars with promising characteristics.
[src:apple/apple] The words "seedling", "pippin", and "kernel" in the name of an apple cultivar suggest that it originated as a seedling.
[src:apple/apple] Apples can also form bud sports (mutations on a single branch).
[src:apple/apple] Some bud sports turn out to be improved strains of the parent cultivar.
[src:apple/apple] Some differ sufficiently from the parent tree to be considered new cultivars.
[src:apple/apple] Apples have been acclimatized in Ecuador at very high altitudes, where they can often, with the needed factors, provide crops twice per year because of constant temperate conditions year-round.
[src:apple/apple] Apples are self-incompatible; they must cross-pollinate to develop fruit.
[src:apple/apple] During the flowering each season, apple growers often utilize pollinators to carry pollen.
[src:apple/apple] Orchard mason bees are also used as supplemental pollinators in commercial orchards.
[src:apple/apple] Bumblebee queens are sometimes present in orchards, but not usually in sufficient number to be significant pollinators.
[src:apple/apple] Cultivars are sometimes classified by the day of peak bloom in the average 30-day blossom period, with pollinizers selected from cultivars within a 6-day overlap period.
[src:apple/apple] One cultivar can be pollinated by a compatible cultivar from the same group or close (A with A, or A with B, but not A with C or D).
[src:apple/apple] Cultivars vary in their yield and the ultimate size of the tree, even when grown on the same rootstock.
[src:apple/apple] Some cultivars, if left unpruned, grow very large—letting them bear more fruit, but making harvesting more difficult.
[src:apple/apple] Depending on tree density (number of trees planted per unit surface area), mature trees typically bear 40–200 kg (90–440 lb) of apples each year, though productivity can be close to zero in poor years.
[src:apple/apple] Apples are harvested using three-point ladders that are designed to fit amongst the branches.
[src:apple/apple] Trees grafted on dwarfing rootstocks bear about 10–80 kg (20–180 lb) of fruit per year.
[src:apple/apple] Some farms with apple orchards open them to the public so consumers can pick their own apples.
[src:apple/apple] Crops ripen at different times of the year according to the cultivar.
[src:apple/apple] Cultivars that yield their crop in the summer include 'Sweet Bough' and 'Duchess'; fall producers include 'Blenheim'; winter producers include 'King', 'Swayzie', and 'Tolman Sweet'.
[src:apple/apple] Commercially, apples can be stored for months in controlled atmosphere chambers.
[src:apple/apple] Apples are commonly stored in chambers with lowered concentrations of oxygen to reduce respiration and slow softening and other changes if the fruit is already fully ripe.
[src:apple/apple] The gas ethylene is used by plants as a hormone which promotes ripening, decreasing the time an apple can be stored.
[src:apple/apple] For storage longer than about six months the apples are picked earlier, before full ripeness, when ethylene production by the fruit is low.
[src:apple/apple] However, in many varieties this increases their sensitivity to carbon dioxide, which also must be controlled.
[src:apple/apple] For home storage, most cultivars of apple can be stored for three weeks in a pantry and four to six weeks from the date of purchase in a refrigerator that maintains 4 to 0 °C (39 to 32 °F).
[src:apple/apple] 'Granny Smith' and 'Fuji') have more than three times the storage life of others.
[src:apple/apple] Non-organic apples may be sprayed with a substance 1-methylcyclopropene blocking the apples' ethylene receptors, temporarily preventing them from ripening.
[src:apple/apple] Among the most serious disease problems is a bacterial disease called fireblight, and three fungal diseases: *Gymnosporangium* rust, black spot, and bitter rot.
[src:apple/apple] Codling moths, and the apple maggots of fruit flies, cause serious damage to apple fruits, making them unsaleable.
[src:apple/apple] Young apple trees are also prone to mammal pests like mice and deer, which feed on the soft bark of the trees, especially in winter.
[src:apple/apple] The larvae of the apple clearwing moth (red-belted clearwing) burrow through the bark and into the phloem of apple trees, potentially causing significant damage.
[src:apple/apple] There are more than 7,500 known cultivars (cultivated varieties) of apples.
[src:apple/apple] Different cultivars are available for temperate and subtropical climates.
[src:apple/apple] The UK's National Fruit Collection in Kent includes over 2,000 apple cultivars.
[src:apple/apple] The University of Reading, responsible for developing the UK national collection database, provides access to search the national collection.
[src:apple/apple] Its work is part of the European Cooperative Programme for Plant Genetic Resources, with 38 countries participating in the Malus/Pyrus work group.
[src:apple/apple] The UK's national fruit collection database contains much information on the characteristics and origin of many apples, including alternative names for what is essentially the same "genetic" apple cultivar.
[src:apple/apple] Most of these cultivars are bred for eating fresh (dessert apples), though some are cultivated specifically for cooking (cooking apples) or producing cider.
[src:apple/apple] Cider apples are typically too tart and astringent to eat fresh, but they give the beverage a rich flavor that dessert apples cannot.
[src:apple/apple] In Europe, apple breeding programs are conducted at places such as Julius Kühn-Institut, the German federal research center for cultivated plants.
[src:apple/apple] In the United States there are many apple breeding programs associated with universities.
[src:apple/apple] For instance, in the East, Cornell University has had a program operating since 1880 in Geneva, New York, while in the West, Washington State University started a program to support their home state's apple industry in 1994.
[src:apple/apple] Released by the University of Minnesota in 1991, the 'Honeycrisp' has become famous for its crispness and juiciness, thereby commanding high market prices.
[src:apple/apple] Unusually for a popular cultivar, the 'Honeycrisp' is not directly related to another popular apple cultivar but instead to two unsuccessful cultivars.
[src:apple/apple] However, it is also difficult to grow and to store, prompting the industry to seek hybrids that not only appeal to consumers but are also less costly for farmers to cultivate and last longer in storage.
[src:apple/apple] By the 2020s, about half of the new apple varieties entering the market in the United States and Canada are 'Honeycrisp' progeny.
[src:apple/apple] Such hybrids include the 'SweeTango' (a cross between the 'Honeycrisp' and the 'Zestar') introduced by the University of Minnesota in 2008 and the 'Cosmic Crisp' (the 'Honeycrisp' and the 'Enterprise') released by Washington State University in 2017.
[src:apple/apple] Commercially popular apple cultivars are soft but crisp.
[src:apple/apple] Other desirable qualities in modern commercial apple breeding are a colorful skin, absence of russeting, ease of shipping, lengthy storage ability, high yields, disease resistance, common apple shape, and developed flavor.
[src:apple/apple] Modern apples are generally sweeter than older cultivars, as popular tastes in apples have varied over time.
[src:apple/apple] Most North Americans and Europeans favor crunchy, sweet, and subacid apples.
[src:apple/apple] Nevertheless, tart apples maintain a strong minority following.
[src:apple/apple] In the United States today, the most popular apple varieties are the 'Ambrosia', 'Honeycrisp', and 'Jazz', according Nielsen data, while in Canada, the 'Honeycrisp', 'Ambrosia', and 'Gala' take the top spots.
[src:apple/apple] Together, these newer varieties have overtaken once dominant cultivars like the 'McIntosh' and the 'Red Delicious' in the North American market.
[src:apple/apple] Extremely sweet apples with barely any acid flavor are popular in Asia, especially the Indian subcontinent.
[src:apple/apple] Old cultivars are often oddly shaped, russeted, and grow in a variety of textures and colors.
[src:apple/apple] Some find them to have better flavor than modern cultivars, but they may have other problems that make them commercially unviable—low yield, disease susceptibility, poor tolerance for storage or transport, or just being the "wrong" size.
[src:apple/apple] A few old cultivars are still produced on a large scale, but many have been preserved by home gardeners and farmers who sell directly to local markets.
[src:apple/apple] Many unusual and locally important cultivars with their own unique taste and appearance exist; apple conservation campaigns have sprung up around the world to preserve such local cultivars from extinction.
[src:apple/apple] In the United Kingdom, old cultivars such as 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Egremont Russet' are still commercially important even though by modern standards they are low yielding and susceptible to disease.
[src:apple/apple] World production of apples in 2023 was 97 million tonnes, with China producing 51% of the total (table).
[src:apple/apple] Secondary producers were the United States, Turkey, and Poland.
[src:apple/apple] Apple seeds contain small amounts of amygdalin, a sugar and cyanide compound known as a cyanogenic glycoside.
[src:apple/apple] Ingesting small amounts of apple seeds causes no ill effects, but consumption of extremely large doses can cause adverse reactions.
[src:apple/apple] It may take several hours before the poison takes effect, as cyanogenic glycosides must be hydrolyzed before the cyanide ion is released.
[src:apple/apple] National Library of Medicine's Hazardous Substances Data Bank records no cases of amygdalin poisoning from consuming apple seeds.
[src:apple/apple] One form of apple allergy, often found in northern Europe, is called birch-apple syndrome and is found in people who are also allergic to birch pollen.
[src:apple/apple] Allergic reactions are triggered by a protein in apples that is similar to birch pollen, and people affected by this protein can also develop allergies to other fruits, nuts, and vegetables.
[src:apple/apple] Reactions, which entail oral allergy syndrome (OAS), generally involve itching and inflammation of the mouth and throat, but in rare cases can also include life-threatening anaphylaxis.
[src:apple/apple] This reaction only occurs when raw fruit is consumed—the allergen is neutralized in the cooking process.
[src:apple/apple] The variety of apple, maturity and storage conditions can change the amount of allergen present in individual fruits.
[src:apple/apple] Long storage times can increase the amount of proteins that cause birch-apple syndrome.
[src:apple/apple] In other areas, such as the Mediterranean, some individuals have adverse reactions to apples because of their similarity to peaches.
[src:apple/apple] This form of apple allergy also includes OAS, but often has more severe symptoms, such as vomiting, abdominal pain and urticaria, and can be life-threatening.
[src:apple/apple] Individuals with this form of allergy can also develop reactions to other fruits and nuts.
[src:apple/apple] Cooking does not break down the protein causing this particular reaction, so affected individuals cannot eat raw or cooked apples.
[src:apple/apple] Freshly harvested, over-ripe fruits tend to have the highest levels of the protein that causes this reaction.
[src:apple/apple] Breeding efforts have yet to produce a hypoallergenic fruit suitable for either of the two forms of apple allergy.
[src:apple/apple] A raw apple is 86% water and 14% carbohydrates, with negligible content of fat and protein (table).
[src:apple/apple] A reference serving of a raw apple with skin weighing 100 g (3.5 oz) provides 52 calories and a moderate content of dietary fiber (table).
[src:apple/apple] Otherwise, there is low content of micronutrients, which are all below 10% of the Daily Value (table).
[src:apple/apple] Apple varieties can be grouped as cooking apples, eating apples, and cider apples, the last so astringent as to be "almost inedible".
[src:apple/apple] Apples are consumed as juice, raw in salads, baked in pies, cooked into sauces and apple butter, or baked.
[src:apple/apple] They are sometimes used as an ingredient in savory foods, such as sausage and stuffing.
[src:apple/apple] Several techniques are used to preserve apples and apple products.
[src:apple/apple] Traditional methods include drying and making apple butter.
[src:apple/apple] Juice and cider are produced commercially; cider is a significant industry in regions such as the West of England and Normandy.
[src:apple/apple] A toffee apple (UK) or caramel apple (US) is a confection made by coating an apple in hot toffee or caramel candy respectively and allowing it to cool.
[src:apple/apple] Apples and honey are a ritual food pairing eaten during the Jewish New Year of Rosh Hashanah.
[src:apple/apple] Apples are an important ingredient in many desserts, such as pies, crumbles, and cakes.
[src:apple/apple] When cooked, some apple cultivars easily form a puree known as apple sauce, which can be cooked down to form a preserve, apple butter.
[src:apple/apple] They are often baked or stewed, and are cooked in some meat dishes.
[src:apple/apple] Apples are milled or pressed to produce apple juice, which may be drunk unfiltered (called apple cider in North America), or filtered.
[src:apple/apple] Filtered juice is often concentrated and frozen, then reconstituted later and consumed.
[src:apple/apple] Apple juice can be fermented to make cider (called hard cider in North America), ciderkin, and vinegar.
[src:apple/apple] Through distillation, various alcoholic beverages can be produced, such as applejack, Calvados, and apple brandy.
[src:apple/apple] Organic apples are commonly produced in the United States.
[src:apple/apple] Due to infestations by key insects and diseases, organic production is difficult in Europe.
[src:apple/apple] The use of pesticides containing chemicals, such as sulfur, copper, microorganisms, viruses, clay powders, or plant extracts (pyrethrum, neem) has been approved by the EU Organic Standing Committee to improve organic yield and quality.
[src:apple/apple] A light coating of kaolin, which forms a physical barrier to some pests, also may help prevent apple sun scalding.
[src:apple/apple] Apple skins and seeds contain polyphenols.
[src:apple/apple] These are oxidised by the enzyme polyphenol oxidase, which causes browning in sliced or bruised apples, by catalyzing the oxidation of phenolic compounds to o-quinones, a browning factor.
[src:apple/apple] Browning reduces apple taste, color, and food value.
[src:apple/apple] Arctic apples, a non-browning group of apples introduced to the United States market in 2019, have been genetically modified to silence the expression of polyphenol oxidase, thereby delaying a browning effect and improving apple eating quality.
[src:apple/apple] The US Food and Drug Administration in 2015, and Canadian Food Inspection Agency in 2017, determined that Arctic apples are as safe and nutritious as conventional apples.
[src:apple/apple] Apple seed oil is obtained by pressing apple seeds for manufacturing cosmetics.
[src:apple/apple] In Norse mythology, the goddess Iðunn is portrayed in the *Prose Edda* (written in the 13th century by Snorri Sturluson) as providing apples to the gods that give them eternal youthfulness.
[src:apple/apple] Ellis Davidson links apples to religious practices in Germanic paganism, from which Norse paganism developed.
[src:apple/apple] She points out that buckets of apples were found in the Oseberg ship burial site in Norway, and that fruits and nuts have been found in the early graves of the Germanic peoples in England and elsewhere in Europe.
[src:apple/apple] The fruits and nuts may have had a symbolic meaning, and nuts are still a recognized symbol of fertility in southwest England.
[src:apple/apple] Rerir's wife's consumption of the apple results in a six-year pregnancy and the birth (by Caesarean section) of their son—the hero Völsung.
[src:apple/apple] Further, Davidson points out the "strange" phrase "Apples of Hel" used in an 11th-century poem by the skald Thorbiorn Brúnarson.
[src:apple/apple] She states this may imply that the apple was thought of by Brúnarson as the food of the dead.
[src:apple/apple] Further, Davidson notes that the potentially Germanic goddess Nehalennia is sometimes depicted with apples and that parallels exist in early Irish stories.
[src:apple/apple] Davidson asserts that while cultivation of the apple in Northern Europe extends back to at least the time of the Roman Empire and came to Europe from the Near East, the native varieties of apple trees growing in Northern Europe are small and bitter.
[src:apple/apple] Apples appear in many religious traditions, including Greek and Roman mythology where it has an ambiguous symbolism of discord, fertility, or courtship.
[src:apple/apple] In Greek mythology, the Greek hero Heracles, as a part of his Twelve Labours, was required to travel to the Garden of the Hesperides and pick the golden apples off the Tree of Life growing at its center.
[src:apple/apple] The Greek goddess of discord, Eris, became disgruntled after she was excluded from the wedding of Peleus and Thetis.
[src:apple/apple] In retaliation, she tossed a golden apple inscribed Καλλίστη (*Kallistē*, "For the most beautiful one"), into the wedding party.
[src:apple/apple] Three goddesses claimed the apple: Hera, Athena, and Aphrodite.
[src:apple/apple] Paris of Troy was appointed to select the recipient.
[src:apple/apple] After being bribed by both Hera and Athena, Aphrodite tempted him with the most beautiful woman in the world, Helen of Sparta.
[src:apple/apple] He awarded the apple to Aphrodite, thus indirectly causing the Trojan War.
[src:apple/apple] The apple was thus considered, in ancient Greece, sacred to Aphrodite.
[src:apple/apple] To throw an apple at someone was to symbolically declare one's love; and similarly, to catch it was to symbolically show one's acceptance of that love.
[src:apple/apple] Atalanta, also of Greek mythology, raced all her suitors in an attempt to avoid marriage.
[src:apple/apple] She outran all but Hippomenes (also known as Melanion, a name possibly derived from *melon*, the Greek word for both "apple" and fruit in general), who defeated her by cunning, not speed.
[src:apple/apple] Hippomenes knew that he could not win in a fair race, so he used three golden apples (gifts of Aphrodite, the goddess of love) to distract Atalanta.
[src:apple/apple] It took all three apples and all of his speed, but Hippomenes was finally successful, winning the race and Atalanta's hand.
[src:apple/apple] In Celtic mythology, the otherworld has many names, including *Emain Ablach*, "Emain of the Apple-trees".
[src:apple/apple] A version of this is Avalon in Arthurian legend, or in Welsh *Ynys Afallon*, "Island of Apples".
[src:apple/apple] In China, apples symbolise peace, since the sounds of the first element ("píng") in the words "apple" (苹果, *Píngguǒ*) and "peace" (平安, *Píng'ān*) are homophonous in Mandarin and Cantonese.
[src:apple/apple] When these two words are combined, the word *Píngānguǒ* (平安果, "Peace apples") is formed.
[src:apple/apple] This association developed further as the name for Christmas Eve in Mandarin is *Píngānyè* (平安夜, "Peaceful/Quiet Evening"), which made the gifting of apples at this season to friends and associates popular, as a way to wish them peace and safety.
[src:apple/apple] Though the forbidden fruit of Eden in the Book of Genesis is not identified, popular Christian tradition has held that it was an apple that Eve coaxed Adam to share with her.
[src:apple/apple] The origin of the popular identification with a fruit unknown in the Middle East in biblical times is found in wordplay with the Latin words *mālum* (an apple) and *mălum* (an evil), each of which is normally written *malum*.
[src:apple/apple] The tree of the forbidden fruit is called "the tree of the knowledge of good and evil" in Genesis 2:17, and the Latin for "good and evil" is *bonum et malum*.
[src:apple/apple] Renaissance painters may also have been influenced by the story of the golden apples in the Garden of Hesperides.
[src:apple/apple] As a result, in the story of Adam and Eve, the apple became a symbol for knowledge, immortality, temptation, the fall of man into sin, and sin itself.
[src:apple/apple] The larynx in the human throat has been called the "Adam's apple" because of a notion that it was caused by the forbidden fruit remaining in the throat of Adam.
[src:apple/apple] The apple as symbol of sexual seduction has been used to imply human sexuality, possibly in an ironic vein.
[src:apple/apple] The proverb, "An apple a day keeps the doctor away", addressing the supposed health benefits of the fruit, has been traced to 19th-century Wales, where the original phrase was "Eat an apple on going to bed, and you'll keep the doctor from earning his bread".
[src:apple/apple] In the 19th century and early 20th, the phrase evolved to "an apple a day, no doctor to pay" and "an apple a day sends the doctor away"; the phrasing now commonly used was first recorded in 1922.
